\begin_layout Subsection
Convexity
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We take a little detour in this section to establish an important result
 in analysis and probability theory: Jensen's inequality.
 The proof of this theorem is remarkably simple once we develop a reasonable
 understanding on the behavior of convex functions; in particular, we need
 to show that convex functions always have support lines.
 This is intuitively obvious, but showing this rigorously requires a bit
 of work, which we do here.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "def:convexFunction"

\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 be a vector space.
 A function 
\begin_inset Formula $f:X\to\R$
\end_inset

 is called convex if for any 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda\in\left[0,1\right]$
\end_inset

 and any 
\begin_inset Formula $x,y\in X$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f\left(\lambda x+\left(1-\lambda\right)y\right)\leq\lambda f\left(x\right)+\left(1-\lambda\right)f\left(y\right).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In elementary calculus, we learnt that convex functions are those that have
 a graph shaped like a smile (concave functions are frowns), and that the
 second derivative of convex functions are positive.
 However, convex functions in general need not be differentiable (
\begin_inset Formula $\lvert x\rvert$
\end_inset

 is convex but not differentiable at zero).
 Convex functions do have the property of 
\emph on
subdifferentiability, 
\emph default
which is basically captures the fact that convex functions with 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

corners
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 can have tangent lines, even if they are not unique.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Lemma
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "lem:convexTangents"

\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $f:\left[a,b\right]\to\R$
\end_inset

 be a convex function.
 Then for any 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\left(a,b\right)$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{f\left(x\right)-f\left(a\right)}{x-a}\leq\frac{f\left(b\right)-f\left(a\right)}{b-a}\leq\frac{f\left(b\right)-f\left(x\right)}{b-x}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda=\frac{b-x}{b-a}$
\end_inset

 and so 
\begin_inset Formula $1-\lambda=\frac{x-a}{b-a}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
f\left(x\right) & -f\left(a\right)=f\left(\lambda a+\left(1-\lambda\right)b\right)-f\left(a\right)\\
 & \leq\lambda f\left(a\right)+\left(1-\lambda\right)f\left(b\right)-f\left(a\right)\\
 & =\left(1-\lambda\right)\left(f\left(b\right)-f\left(a\right)\right)\\
 & =\frac{x-a}{b-a}\left(f\left(b\right)-f\left(a\right)\right)
\end{align*}

\end_inset

so rearranging yields the first inequality.
 The second inequality is similarly deduced by noticing that 
\begin_inset Formula $f\left(b\right)-f\left(x\right)\geq f\left(b\right)-\lambda f\left(a\right)-\left(1-\lambda\right)f\left(b\right)=\lambda\left(f\left(b\right)-f\left(a\right)\right)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now let 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{0}\in\left(a,b\right)$
\end_inset

 be fixed and define
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
m^{-}\left(x_{0}\right) & :=\sup_{\eta\in\left(a,b\right),\eta<x_{0}}\frac{f\left(x_{0}\right)-f\left(\eta\right)}{x_{0}-\eta}\\
m^{+}\left(x_{0}\right) & :=\inf_{\xi\in\left(a,b\right),\xi>x_{0}}\frac{f\left(\xi\right)-f\left(x_{0}\right)}{\xi-x_{0}}.
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Proposition
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "prop:convexLeftRightDerivative"

\end_inset

For any 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{0}\in\left(a,b\right)$
\end_inset

 and any convex function 
\begin_inset Formula $f:\left[a,b\right]\to\R$
\end_inset

 , 
\begin_inset Formula $m^{-}\left(x_{0}\right)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $m^{+}\left(x_{0}\right)$
\end_inset

 are finite and 
\begin_inset Formula $m^{-}\left(x_{0}\right)\leq m^{+}\left(x_{0}\right)$
\end_inset

 with equality holding if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is differentiable at 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{0}$
\end_inset

 in which case 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
m^{-}\left(x_{0}\right)=m^{+}\left(x_{0}\right)=f^{\prime}\left(x_{0}\right).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
Fix 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{0}\in\left(a,b\right)$
\end_inset

 and note that by our Lemma 
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
in our lemma 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 are arbitrary.
 Here we are applying the Lemma to 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{0}\in\left(\eta,b\right)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{0}\in\left(a,\xi\right)$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

, for 
\begin_inset Formula $a<\eta<x_{0}<\xi<b$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{f\left(x_{0}\right)-f\left(\eta\right)}{x_{0}-\eta}\leq\frac{f\left(b\right)-f\left(x_{0}\right)}{b-x_{0}}
\]

\end_inset

and so its supremum 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
m^{-}\left(x_{0}\right)\leq\frac{f\left(b\right)-f\left(x_{0}\right)}{b-x_{0}}
\]

\end_inset

and similarly 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{f\left(\xi\right)-f\left(x_{0}\right)}{\xi-x_{0}}\geq\frac{f\left(x_{0}\right)-f\left(a\right)}{x_{0}-a}
\]

\end_inset

and so 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
m^{+}\left(x_{0}\right)\geq\frac{f\left(x_{0}\right)-f\left(a\right)}{x_{0}-a}.
\]

\end_inset

Next, note that applying the Lemma to 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{0}\in\left(\eta,\xi\right)$
\end_inset

 tells us that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{f\left(x_{0}\right)-f\left(\eta\right)}{x_{0}-\eta}\leq\frac{f\left(\xi\right)-f\left(x_{0}\right)}{\xi-x_{0}}
\]

\end_inset

and so
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
m^{-}\left(x_{0}\right)\leq m^{+}\left(x_{0}\right).
\]

\end_inset

Finally, apply the Lemma to 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{2}\in\left(\eta_{1},x_{0}\right)$
\end_inset

 to deduce that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{f\left(x_{0}\right)-f\left(\eta_{2}\right)}{x_{0}-\eta_{2}}\geq\frac{f\left(x_{0}\right)-f\left(\eta_{1}\right)}{x_{0}-\eta_{1}}
\]

\end_inset

which means that 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{f\left(x_{0}\right)-f\left(\eta\right)}{x_{0}-\eta}$
\end_inset

 is increasing in 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta<x_{0}$
\end_inset

 and is bounded above and so
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\lim_{\eta\to x_{0}^{-}}\frac{f\left(x_{0}\right)-f\left(\eta\right)}{x_{0}-\eta}=m^{-}\left(x_{0}\right).
\]

\end_inset

Similarly, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\lim_{\xi\to x_{0}^{+}}\frac{f\left(\xi\right)-f\left(x_{0}\right)}{\xi-x_{0}}=m^{+}\left(x_{0}\right)
\]

\end_inset

and so our 
\begin_inset Formula $m^{-}$
\end_inset

and 
\begin_inset Formula $m^{+}$
\end_inset

 are simply left and right hand derivatives and our claim follows.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now we can construct tangent lines to convex functions in the following
 sense
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proposition
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "prop:subderivatives"

\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $f:\left[a,b\right]\to\R$
\end_inset

 be a convex function.
 For any 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{0}\in\left(a,b\right),$
\end_inset

 for any 
\begin_inset Formula $m\in\left[m^{-}\left(x_{0}\right),m^{+}\left(x_{0}\right)\right],$
\end_inset

we have that
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
l\left(x\right):=f\left(x_{0}\right)+m\left(x-x_{0}\right)\leq f\left(x\right).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
Note that for 
\begin_inset Formula $x>x_{0}$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{f\left(x\right)-f\left(x_{0}\right)}{x-x_{0}}\geq m^{+}\left(x_{0}\right)\geq m
\]

\end_inset

and if 
\begin_inset Formula $x<x_{0}$
\end_inset

 then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{f\left(x_{0}\right)-f\left(x\right)}{x_{0}-x}\leq m^{-}\left(x_{0}\right)\leq m.
\]

\end_inset

 The case of 
\begin_inset Formula $x=x_{0}$
\end_inset

 is trivial.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Remark*
The interval 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[m^{-}\left(x_{0}\right),m^{+}\left(x_{0}\right)\right]$
\end_inset

 is called the set of 
\emph on
subderivatives 
\emph default
of 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{0}$
\end_inset

.
 It should be clear that 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is differentiable at 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{0}$
\end_inset

 if and only if the set is a singleton.
 The function 
\begin_inset Formula $l$
\end_inset

 is called a 
\emph on
supporting line 
\emph default
at 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{0}$
\end_inset

.
 More generally, a supporting line 
\begin_inset Formula $l$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{0}$
\end_inset

 is any affine function that satisfies 
\begin_inset Formula $l\left(x_{0}\right)=f\left(x_{0}\right)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $l\left(x\right)\leq f\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

 for every 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\left(a,b\right)$
\end_inset

.
 A convex function on 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[a,b\right]$
\end_inset

 has at least one supporting line at every point in 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(a,b\right)$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Note that the existence of left and right derivatives at a point implies
 continuity at that point.
 This implies that convex functions on an interval are continuous.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proposition
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "prop:leftRightDerivativeImpliesContinuity"

\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $f:\left[a,b\right]\to\R$
\end_inset

 be a function such that for a point 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{0}\in\left(a,b\right)$
\end_inset

