\begin_layout Standard
In the context of 
\begin_inset Formula $L^{p}$
\end_inset

 spaces, we replace the notion of boundedness (i.e.
 the quality of a function in a space being bounded) with the related notion
 of 
\emph on
essentially boundedness.
 
\emph default
A function is said to be essentially bounded if it is bounded except on
 a null set.
 Then the space of essentially bounded functions from a measure space 
\begin_inset Formula $\measurespace$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\R,\borel\left(\R\right)\right)$
\end_inset

is denoted 
\begin_inset Formula $\Lp{\infty}{\X,\F,\mu}$
\end_inset

.
 This space comes equipped with a (semi) norm 
\begin_inset Formula $\pnorm{\cdot}{\infty}$
\end_inset

 so that for 
\begin_inset Formula $f\in\Lp{\infty}{\mu},$
\end_inset

we have that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\pnorm f{\infty}:=\inf\left\{ C\in\R\mid\mu\left(\left\{ \lvert f\rvert>C\right\} \right)=0\right\} .
\]

\end_inset

To see this is indeed a semi-norm, we can verify that non-negativity is
 satisfied by definition.
 To see homogeneity, observe that for any 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha\neq0$
\end_inset

, the collection 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ C\in\R\mid\mu\left(\lvert\alpha f\rvert>C\right)\right\} =\left\{ \lvert\alpha\rvert C\in\R\mid\mu\left(\lvert f\rvert>C\right)\right\} $
\end_inset

 and so we have homogeneity.
 For the triangle inequality, consider the fact that for any 
\begin_inset Formula $C\in\R$
\end_inset

 and any 
\begin_inset Formula $f,g\in\Lp{\infty}{\mu}$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $\lvert f\left(x\right)\rvert\leq\pnorm f{\infty},\lvert g\left(x\right)\rvert\leq\pnorm g{\infty}$
\end_inset

 for almost all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\X$
\end_inset

 and so
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\lvert f\left(x\right)+g\left(x\right)\rvert\leq\lvert f\left(x\right)\rvert+\lvert g\left(x\right)\rvert\leq\pnorm f{\infty}+\pnorm g{\infty}
\]

\end_inset

almost everywhere.
 In words, 
\begin_inset Formula $\pnorm f{\infty}+\pnorm g{\infty}$
\end_inset

 is an 
\emph on
essential upper-bound 
\emph default
for 
\begin_inset Formula $\lvert f\left(x\right)+g\left(x\right)\rvert$
\end_inset

 and so 
\begin_inset Formula $\pnorm f{\infty}+\pnorm g{\infty}\in\left\{ C\in\R\mid\mu\left(\left\{ \lvert f+g\rvert>C\right\} \right)=0\right\} .$
\end_inset

 The inequality then follows since 
\begin_inset Formula $\pnorm{f+g}{\infty}$
\end_inset

 is the infimum of that set.
 The notation 
\begin_inset Formula $\Lp{\infty}{\mu}$
\end_inset

 of course deserves some scrutiny; one potential justification for the choice
 of notation is the following result.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proposition
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "prop:limLp"

\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\measurespace$
\end_inset

 be a measure space and let 
\begin_inset Formula $f\in\cap_{p\in\N}\Lp p{\mu}.$
\end_inset

Then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\lim_{p\to\infty}\pnorm fp=\pnorm f{\infty}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
First, suppose that 
\begin_inset Formula $\pnorm f{\infty}<\infty.$
\end_inset

 Then, for any sequence 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{n}\to\infty,$
\end_inset

 we have that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\pnorm f{p+q_{n}} & =\lebInt{\mu}{\lvert f\rvert^{p+q_{n}}}^{\frac{1}{p+q_{n}}}\\
 & \leq\lebInt{\mu}{\lVert f\rVert_{\infty}^{q_{n}}\lvert f\rvert^{p}}^{\frac{1}{p+q_{n}}}\\
 & =\lVert f\rVert_{\infty}^{\frac{q_{n}}{p+q_{n}}}\lebInt{\mu}{\lvert f\rvert^{p}}^{\frac{1}{p+q_{n}}}
\end{align*}

\end_inset

where we used the fact that 
\begin_inset Formula $\lvert f\rvert\leq\pnorm f{\infty}$
\end_inset

 almost everywhere and the monotonicity and linearity of the integral.
 Taking lim-sups
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
We don't know if the limit on the left side exists; the right-hand side
 has a proper limit and so is equal to its lim-sup.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 on both sides we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\limsup_{q_{n}\to\infty}\pnorm f{p+q_{n}}\leq\pnorm f{\infty}.
\]

\end_inset

Conversely, note that for any 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon>0$
\end_inset

, we have the fact that 
\begin_inset Formula $\lvert f\rvert\geq\left(\pnorm f{\infty}-\epsilon\right)$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\indicate\left\{ \lvert f\rvert>\pnorm f{\infty}-\epsilon\right\} $
\end_inset

 and so since p-norms respect monotonicty, we have that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\pnorm fp & \geq\pnorm{\left(\pnorm f{\infty}-\epsilon\right)\indicate\left\{ \lvert f\rvert>\pnorm f{\infty}-\epsilon\right\} }p\\
 & =\lvert\pnorm f{\infty}-\epsilon\rvert\mu\left(\lvert f\rvert>\pnorm f{\infty}-\epsilon\right)^{\frac{1}{p}}
\end{align*}

\end_inset

where we have used homogeneity in the second line.
 Note that the right hand side is finite by Markov's inequality since 
\begin_inset Formula $f\in\Lp1{\mu}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\pnorm f{\infty}<\infty$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Formula $\mu\left(\lvert f\rvert>\pnorm f{\infty}-\epsilon\right)\leq\frac{\lebInt{\mu}{\lvert f\rvert}}{\pnorm f{\infty}-\epsilon}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

 and positive by the fact that 
\begin_inset Formula $\pnorm f{\infty}$
\end_inset

is an essential supremum so any smaller real number cannot be an essential
 upper bound.
 Letting 
\begin_inset Formula $p\to\infty,\epsilon\to0$
\end_inset

 on the right hand side ( while taking a lim-inf on the left), we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\liminf_{p\to\infty}\pnorm fp\geq\pnorm f{\infty}
\]

\end_inset

which completes the proof for the essentially bounded case.
\end_layout

