\begin_layout Proof
In order to establish multiplicative linearity on 
\begin_inset Formula $\R$
\end_inset

, we shall first demonstrate it on natural numbers 
\begin_inset Formula $\N$
\end_inset

, then on integers 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathds{Z},$
\end_inset

then on the rationals 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathds{Q}$
\end_inset

 and finally the entire real line.
 First, we show that for any 
\begin_inset Formula $n\in\N:\left(nv,w\right)=n\left(v,w\right).$
\end_inset

 This follows from induction on additive linearity since
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\left(nv,w\right) & =\left(\sum_{i=1}^{n}v,w\right)\\
 & =\sum_{i=1}^{n}\left(v,w\right)\\
 & =n\left(v,w\right).
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Next, to show that multiplicative linearity holds over 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathds{Z},$
\end_inset

 all we have to show is that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left(0v,w\right)=0
\]

\end_inset

and
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left(-v,w\right)=-\left(v,w\right).
\]

\end_inset

The first follows on inspection; for the second, note
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\left(-v,w\right) & =\frac{1}{4}\left(\pnorm{w-v}{}^{2}-\pnorm{-\left(v+w\right)}{}^{2}\right)\\
 & =\frac{1}{4}\left(\pnorm{v-w}{}^{2}-\pnorm{v+w}{}^{2}\right)\\
 & =-\left(v,w\right)
\end{align*}

\end_inset

where the second equality follows from absolute homogeneity of norms.
 To extend the multiplicative linearity to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathds{Q}$
\end_inset

, consider an arbitrary 
\begin_inset Formula $q\in\mathds{Q}$
\end_inset

 and note that by definition 
\begin_inset Formula $q=\frac{a}{b},\left(a,b\right)\in\mathds{Z}\times\left(\mathds{Z}\setminus\left\{ 0\right\} \right)$
\end_inset

 and so
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\left(qv,w\right) & =\left(\frac{a}{b}v,w\right)\\
 & =a\left(\frac{v}{b},w\right)\\
 & =\frac{a}{4}\left(\pnorm{\frac{v}{b}+w}{}^{2}-\pnorm{\frac{v}{b}-w}{}^{2}\right)\\
 & =\frac{a}{4}\left(\pnorm{\frac{b}{b}\left(\frac{v}{b}+w\right)}{}^{2}-\pnorm{\frac{b}{b}\left(\frac{v}{b}-w\right)}{}^{2}\right)\\
 & =\frac{a}{4b^{2}}\left(\pnorm{v+bw}{}^{2}-\pnorm{v-bw}{}^{2}\right)\\
 & =\frac{a}{b^{2}}\left(v,bw\right)\\
 & =\frac{a}{b}\left(v,w\right)\\
 & =q\left(v,w\right)
\end{align*}

\end_inset

where we used the linearity on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathds{Z}$
\end_inset

 (and symmetry) in the second and second-to-last equalities, and the absolute
 homogeneity of norms in the fifth equality.
 Finally, to extend this linearity to all of 
\begin_inset Formula $\R$
\end_inset

, let 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha\in\R$
\end_inset

 be unspecified and observe that by the density of rational numbers in 
\begin_inset Formula $\R$
\end_inset

, there exists a sequence 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ q_{n}\right\} \in\mathds{Q}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\lim_{n\to\infty}q_{n}=\alpha$
\end_inset

 and so, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\left(\alpha v,w\right) & =\left(\lim_{n\to\infty}q_{n}v,w\right)\\
 & =\lim_{n\to\infty}\left(q_{n}v,w\right)\\
 & =\lim_{n\to\infty}q_{n}\left(v,w\right)\\
 & =\alpha\left(v,w\right)
\end{align*}

\end_inset

where the second equality follows by Lemma 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "lem:continuityNorm"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 and the third by our linearity result on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathds{Q}.$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
Together, we have shown that our function 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\cdot,\cdot\right):V\times V\longrightarrow\R$
\end_inset

 satisfies all the properties of the inner product, thus completing the
 proof.
\end_layout

